{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ea89594b-1bf6-48e4-bc0c-cc2f40ecc03e","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, so you can use the modern patterns:\n\n### Recommended approach\n\n**Constructor injection** (MSTest 3.3+) with a **primary constructor** (C# 12):\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n{\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // Synchronous setup\n        // ...\n\n        // Asynchronous setup\n        await SomeServiceAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task ExampleTest()\n    {\n        testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `TestContext` is injected via the primary constructor — no property setter needed.\n- `[TestInitialize]` can return `Task` for async work; put sync setup in the same method.\n- `[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]` also support `async Task` signatures if you need class-level lifecycle hooks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8acd5558-172a-4beb-8b85-c64b7b7e7077","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection** — Use a constructor parameter or the `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest v3+, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization** — `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization** — `[TestInitialize]` can be async (return `Task`).\n\nActually, let me think about what's the most modern approach in MSTest 3.x:\n\n\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor or property\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports async methods\n- `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` also support async\n\nThe recommended modern pattern uses a property-based `TestContext` with an async `[TestInitialize]` method that handles setup operations.\n\nFor MSTest 3.3+, constructor injection is also available, including primary constructor syntax with C# 12, allowing you to inject `TestContext` directly into the class declaration and use it throughout your test methods. The cleanest approach is to use a single async `[TestInitialize]` method that handles both synchronous and asynchronous setup work, especially with MSTest 3.3+ supporting constructor injection of `TestContext` through C# 12 primary constructors.","outputTokens":1038,"requestId":"A042:2FE433:D8C005:FE11DA:69FE8EC4"},"id":"d08c73dc-d72c-42f8-b3c1-66ac3d92c3c3","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:33:12.509Z","parentId":"c7ae8cab-d2fe-44bd-81e2-e01f768652d1"}
